    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1964-06-08T17:07:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1964-06-08T17:07:00-05:00" n="39"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d39">
                <head>39. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in Iran</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d39fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, POL 7 IRAN. Confidential. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_TMG1"
                            >Tiger</persName> on June 5, cleared by Department of State Deputy
                        Executive Secretary John A. McKesson and <persName corresp="#p_KRW2"
                            >Komer</persName>, and approved by <persName corresp="#p_TPH2"
                            >Talbot</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1964-06-08T18:07:00-04:00">June 8, 1964, 6:07 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>914. Shah’s Visit. Presidential meeting and White House luncheon proceeded in
                    atmosphere great warmth and cordiality. In meeting, Shah devoted considerable
                    attention to: Arab designs on Khuzistan, which he said now backed by Khrushchev,
                    who anxious deny oil to West; consequent need enhanced Iranian defensive
                    capabilities; suitability Bandar Abbas for U.S. base use; fears that oil
                    companies would give preferential treatment Arab producers now that <gloss
                        target="#t_OPEC1">OPEC</gloss> an “instrument of Arab imperialism.”
                    President complimented the Shah on his reform measures, calling Iran “brightest
                    spot in the Middle East”. He urged on Shah need to keep up pace of modernization
                    which never-ending process even in U.S. <pb facs="0109" n="81" xml:id="pg_81"/>
                    He also sought to play down extent of Arab military threat. President told Shah
                    we would speak to oil companies about Shah’s misgivings. Shah’s luncheon toast
                    consisted of ringing reaffirmation firm commitment to West.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="strong">
                            <persName corresp="#p_HWA2">Harriman</persName>
                        </hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
